1275","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","circa 1341":"circa 1341","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","circa 1317":"circa 1317","circa 1336":"circa 1336","circa 1335":"circa 1335","circa 1334":"circa 1334","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wighill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wighill, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wighill, Yorkshire, England":"Wighill, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"circa 1317–":"about 1317–Deceased","1317–Female":"1317–Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1315–1377":"1315–1377","1335–1391":"1335–1391","1336–1336":"1336–1336","1341–Male":"1341–Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1275":"1275","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","circa 1341":"about 1341","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","circa 1317":"about 1317","circa 1336":"about 1336","circa 1335":"about 1335","circa 1334":"about 1334","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wighill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wighill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wighill, Yorkshire, England":"Wighill, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Denton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called. The vast majority, including those in Cambridgeshire, Cumbria, Dumfries, Durham, Kent, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Oxfordshire, Sussex, and Yorkshire are named from Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ (see   Dean   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. An isolated example in Northamptonshire appears in the Domesday Book as <i>Dodintone</i> meaning ‘enclosure, settlement associated with <i>Dodda</i> or <i>Dudda</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dean","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":11,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":20,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":65,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Denton was born about 1317, in Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Hugh Denton and NN NN. She married Adam Copley about 1334, in Wighill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"circa 1317–":"umbes 1317–Surnud","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1315–1377":"1315–1377","1335–1391":"1335–1391","1336–1336":"1336–1336","1341–Male":"1341–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1275":"1275","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","13